:3 \sin(x) + 3 = 2 \cos^{2}(x)
-1/6*pi+2*k*pi,7/6*pi+2*k*pi,3/2*pi+2*k*pi
3
2*k*pi
2 \sin^{2}(x) + 3 \sin(x) + 1 = 0 \rightarrow \left( 2 \sin(x)+1\right) \left(\sin(x)+1 \right)=0
\left[ \begin{array}{lll} x_{1} & = & \frac{-1}{6} \pi + 2k\pi \\ x_{2} & = & \frac{7}{6} \pi + 2k\pi \\ x_{3} & = & \frac{3}{2} \pi + 2k\pi \end{array} \right.
\sin^{2}(x)+\cos^{2}(x)=1 \rightarrow \cos^{2}(x)=1-\sin^{2}(x)

:- \sin(x) + 1 = 2 \cos^{2}(x)
-1/6*pi+2*k*pi,7/6*pi+2*k*pi,1/2*pi+2*k*pi		
3
2*k*pi
